Introduction¶

In today's data-driven world, machine learning has become an essential tool for making sense of large amounts of data. The ability to build accurate predictive models from data has numerous applications across industries, from finance and healthcare to marketing and cybersecurity. For my first assignment in this course, I will be exploring the "Heart Attack Analysis & Prediction" dataset created by Rashik Rahman and sourced from Kaggle. Using various machine learning techniques, I will make class label predictions based on the data in the dataset. The main objective of this dataset is to evaluate the impact of various contributors on one's health and the likelihood of heart attack, which will be the target variable for this analysis. To evaluate the effectiveness of the models, I will compare and evaluate the results against industry-standard metrics, including accuracy score, area under the curve values and confusion matrices.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rashikrahmanpritom/heart-attack-analysis-prediction-dataset

Alogorithms¶

The machine learning algorithms that will be executed on the Heart Attack Analysis & Prediction dataset are Support Vector Machines, Decision Trees, and Random Forests.

Support Vector Machines

: SVM is a supervised machine learning algorithm used for classification and regression tasks. It works by finding the best hyperplane that separates the data into different classes. It tries to maximize the margin between the hyperplane and the closest data points of each class. SVM can handle both linear and non-linear data, and is particularly effective for high-dimensional data.

Decision Trees

: Decision Trees are a simple yet powerful classification algorithm that work by recursively splitting the data based on the features that provide the most information gain. Each split divides the data into two or more subgroups, with the goal of eventually producing a set of homogeneous groups. Decision Trees are easy to interpret and visualize, but they can suffer from overfitting and lack of generalization.

Random Forests

: Random Forests is an ensemble learning method that combines multiple decision trees to improve the overall accuracy and robustness of the model. The individual trees in a Random Forest are constructed using random subsets of the data and features, and their results are aggregated to produce the final prediction. This method reduces the risk of overfitting and improves the ability of the model to generalize to new data.

Summary of Variables in Heart Attack Prediction Dataset¶

Age : Age of the patient

Sex : Sex of the patient

exang: exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)

slp: slope

caa: number of major vessels

cp : Chest Pain type chest pain type

Value 1: typical angina
Value 2: atypical angina
Value 3: non-anginal pain
Value 4: asymptomatic

trtbps : resting blood pressure (in mm Hg)

chol : cholestoral in mg/dl fetched via BMI sensor

thall: thalium stress test ~ (0.3)

fbs : (fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl)

1 = true; 0 = false

rest_ecg : resting electrocardiographic results

Value 0: normal
Value 1: having ST-T wave abnormality (T wave inversions and/or ST elevation or depression of > 0.05 mV)
Value 2: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes' criteria

thalach : maximum heart rate achieved

target:

0= less chance of heart attack 
1= more chance of heart attack

sourced from Kaggle(https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rashikrahmanpritom/heart-attack-analysis-prediction-dataset)

6. Modelling¶

In this code, we are importing and setting up several models for our data. We have imported the RobustScaler from the sklearn library, which is a method for scaling data in order to remove the effect of outliers. We are also importing three different models: SVM (Support Vector Machine), Random Forest Classifier, and Decision Tree Classifier. These are all commonly used models for classification tasks.

We have also imported some metrics for evaluating the performance of our models. The metrics we have chosen to use are accuracy score, confusion matrix, and ROC AUC score. The accuracy score measures the percentage of correctly classified instances, the confusion matrix shows the number of true and false positive and negative classifications, and the ROC AUC score is a measure of the overall performance of a classification model.

After obtaining a less-than-satisfactory test accuracy score using the Support Vector Machine (SVM) model, I decided to scale the data to see if it would improve the model's performance. To do this, I imported the RobustScaler class from the scikit-learn library and applied it to the training and testing sets.

Scaling the data is important because some machine learning algorithms, such as SVM, are sensitive to unscaled data. This can result in inaccurate predictions and poor model performance. By applying RobustScaler, I was able to normalize the features in the dataset and bring them all to a similar scale, ensuring that the SVM model was working with appropriately scaled data.

After scaling the data, I created a new SVM model and trained it on the scaled training data. I then used this model to make predictions on the scaled test data and evaluated its accuracy using the accuracy_score function. Additionally, I calculated the ROC AUC score and created a confusion matrix to further evaluate the model's performance.

7. Discussion¶

Based on the performance of each model, it appears that the Random Forest model performed the best, followed by the SVM model and then the Decision Tree model. The Random Forest model achieved an accuracy score of 88%, and was able to correctly predict 25 negative samples and 29 positive samples, with only 4 negative samples and 3 positive samples misclassified. This model uses an ensemble of decision trees, which makes it more robust and less prone to overfitting than a single decision tree. The SVM model achieved an accuracy score of 85%, and was able to correctly predict 23 negative samples and 30 positive samples, with only 6 negative samples and 2 positive samples misclassified. This model works well with high-dimensional data, and can handle non-linear relationships between the features and the target variable. The Decision Tree model achieved an accuracy score of 83%, and was able to correctly predict 24 positive samples and 26 negative samples, with 8 positive samples and 3 negative samples misclassified. This model tends to overfit to the training data, and may not generalize well to new data.

In conclusion, Random Forest appears to be the most effective model for predicting heart attacks in the provided dataset due to its ability to manage non-linear correlations between the target variable and the features. As an ensemble model, Random Forest builds several decision trees by utilizing random subsets of the data and features and merges their outcomes to deliver the final prediction. This characteristic decreases the probability of overfitting, a common issue with Decision Trees. Additionally, the Random Forest algorithm overcomes many issues associated with individual decision trees by introducing randomness and aggregation into the equation. Each tree is built independently using a random portion of the data and a random subset of the features at each node, with predictions made for each tree. For classification problems, the most frequent prediction is used, while for regression problems, the average prediction from all the individual trees is used as the output value. As more trees are added to the model, a broader range of data is considered, and more features are used, resulting in a robust, aggregated model.
